0–1182","1140–1168":"1140–1168","1155–1215":"1155–1215","1140–1182":"1140–1182","Abt 1140":"omkring 1140","1215":"1215","ABT 1155":"omkring 1155","1168":"1168","1155":"1155","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","Salford, Oxfordshire, England":"Salford, Oxfordshire, England","Salford, Oxfordshire":"Salford, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1140–1182":"circa 1140–1182","1140–1168":"1140–1168","1155–1215":"1155–1215","1140–1182":"1140–1182","Abt 1140":"circa 1140","1215":"1215","ABT 1155":"circa 1155","1168":"1168","1155":"1155","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","Salford, Oxfordshire, England":"Salford, Oxfordshire, England","Salford, Oxfordshire":"Salford, Oxfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1140–1182":"about 1140–1182","1140–1168":"1140–1168","1155–1215":"1155–1215","1140–1182":"1140–1182","Abt 1140":"about 1140","1215":"1215","ABT 1155":"about 1155","1168":"1168","1155":"1155","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","Salford, Oxfordshire, England":"Salford, Oxfordshire, England","Salford, Oxfordshire":"Salford, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Turberville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name, probably from Thouberville (Eure), or possibly from Trubleville (Seine-Maritime), both in France. The two may have been confused in surname usage."],"variants":[{"name":"Torbet","meanings":["Scottish:","from the Anglo-Norman and Middle English personal name <i>T(h)urbert</i>, <i>T(h)orbert</i>, a hybrid of Old Norse <i>Thorr</i> ‘Thor’, the name of the god of thunder, + ancient Germanic <i>-berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. The name was probably formed on the Continent; see   Turberville  .","perhaps in some cases a nickname from Old French and Middle English <i>turbot</i>, <i>turbut</i> ‘turbot’, for someone who caught or sold or resembled this fish."]},{"name":"Turbyfill","meanings":["Altered form of English   Turberville  ."]},{"name":"Tuberville","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Turberville  . This form of the surname is very rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Turville","meanings":["English (Surrey and Hampshire; of Norman origin):","habitational name from Tourville‐la‐Campagne (Eure, France). The placename derives from the Old Norse personal name <i>Thórr</i> + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘farmstead, estate’ (from Latin <i>villa</i>).","occasionally a shortened form of   Turberville  ."]},{"name":"Turbeville","meanings":["English: variant of   Turberville  ."]},{"name":"Troublefield","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Turberville  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Turberville was born about 1140, in Salford, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 daughter with Eleanor de Norris. He died in 1182, in Salford, Oxfordshire, England, at the age of 43."},"et":{"Abt 1140–1182":"umbes 1140–1182","1140–1168":"1140–1168","1155–1215":"1155–1215","1140–1182":"1140–1182","Abt 1140":"umbes 1140","1215":"1215","ABT 1155":"umbes 1155","1168":"1168","1155":"1155","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","Salford, Oxfordshire, England":"Salford, Oxfordshire, England","Salford, Oxfordshire":"Salford, Oxfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1140–1182":"noin 1140–1182","1140–1168":"1140–1168","1155–1215":"1155–1215","1140–1182":"1140–1182","Abt 1140":"noin 1140","1215":"1215","ABT 1155":"noin 1155","1168":"1168","1155":"1155","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","Salford, Oxfordshire, England":"Salford, Oxfordshire, England","Salford, Oxfordshire":"Salford, Oxfordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1140–1182":"environ 1140–1182","1140–1168":"1140–1168","1155–1215":"1155–1215","1140–1182":"1140–1182","Abt 1140":"environ 1140","1215":"1215","ABT 1155":"environ 1155","1168":"1168","1155":"1155","1140":"1140","1182":"1182","Salford, Oxfordshire, England":"Salford, Oxfordshire, Angleterre","Salford, Oxfordshire":"Salford, Oxfordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Robert de Turberville est né environ 1140, à Salford, Oxfordshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Eleanor de Norris. Il est décédé en 1182, à Salford, Oxfordshire, Angleterre, à l’âge de 43 ans."},"de":{"Abt 1140–1182":"um 1140–1182","1140–1168":"1140–1168","11